{"parse":{"title":"Absolute construction","pageid":28428537,"revid":833121857,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In linguistics, an <b>absolute construction</b> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Grammatical_construction\" title=\"Grammatical construction\">grammatical construction</a> standing apart from a normal or usual syntactical relation with other words or sentence elements. It can be a <a href=\"/wiki/Non-finite_clause\" title=\"Non-finite clause\">non-finite clause</a> that is <a href=\"/wiki/Dependent_clause\" title=\"Dependent clause\">subordinate</a> in form and modifies an entire sentence, an adjective or possessive pronoun standing alone without a modified <a href=\"/wiki/Substantive\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Substantive\">substantive</a>, or a <a href=\"/wiki/Transitive_verb\" title=\"Transitive verb\">transitive verb</a> when its object is implied but not stated.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Merriam-Webster&#39;s_Collegiate_Dictionary_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Merriam-Webster&#39;s_Collegiate_Dictionary-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-American_Heritage_Dictionary_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-American_Heritage_Dictionary-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-CGEL_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CGEL-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-AHBEU_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AHBEU-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>  The term <i>absolute</i> derives from Latin <i>absol\u016btum</i>, meaning \"loosened from\" or \"separated\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Wheelock_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Wheelock-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Because the non-finite clause, called the <b>absolute clause</b> (or simply the <b>absolute</b>), is not semantically attached to any single element in the sentence, it is easily confused with a <a href=\"/wiki/Dangling_participle\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Dangling participle\">dangling participle</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-AHBEU_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AHBEU-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>  The difference is that the <a href=\"/wiki/Participial_phrase\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Participial phrase\">participial phrase</a> of a dangling participle is intended to modify a particular noun, but is instead erroneously attached to a different noun, whereas a participial phrase serving as an absolute clause is not intended to modify any noun at all.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#English\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">English</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Latin\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Latin</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Other_Indo-European_languages\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Other Indo-European languages</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"English\">English</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Absolute_construction&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: English\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>While the absolute construction is not particularly common in modern English and is generally more often seen in writing than in speech, it may be spoken as one of several fixed expressions:<sup id=\"cite_ref-AHBEU_4-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AHBEU-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<ul><li><i>Barring bad weather</i>, we plan to go to the beach tomorrow.</li>\n<li><i>All things considered</i>, it's not a bad idea.</li>\n<li><i>This being the case</i>, let us go.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Merriam-Webster&#39;s_Collegiate_Dictionary_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Merriam-Webster&#39;s_Collegiate_Dictionary-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><i>The referee having finally arrived</i>, the game began.<sup id=\"cite_ref-American_Heritage_Dictionary_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-American_Heritage_Dictionary-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Latin\">Latin</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Absolute_construction&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Latin\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Absolute clauses appear in Latin with the modifying participle in the <a href=\"/wiki/Ablative_case\" title=\"Ablative case\">ablative case</a>; for this reason they are referred to as <a href=\"/wiki/Ablative_absolute\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ablative absolute\">ablative absolutes</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Wheelock_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Wheelock-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>  An ablative absolute describes some general circumstance under which the action of a sentence occurs.  When translated into English, ablative absolutes are often translated as \"with [noun] [participle]\":\n</p>\n<ul><li><i>Urbe capta</i> Aeneas fugit.<br /><i>With the city captured</i>, Aeneas fled.</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Other_Indo-European_languages\">Other Indo-European languages</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Absolute_construction&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Other Indo-European languages\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Absolute constructions occur with other <a href=\"/wiki/Grammatical_case\" title=\"Grammatical case\">grammatical cases</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Indo-European_languages\" title=\"Indo-European languages\">Indo-European languages</a>, such as <a href=\"/wiki/Accusative_absolute\" title=\"Accusative absolute\">accusative absolute</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Greek_language\" title=\"Greek language\">Greek</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/German_language\" title=\"German language\">German</a> and Latin, <a href=\"/wiki/Genitive_absolute\" title=\"Genitive absolute\">genitive absolute</a> in Greek, dative absolute in <a href=\"/wiki/Gothic_language\" title=\"Gothic language\">Gothic</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Old_Church_Slavonic\" title=\"Old Church Slavonic\">Old Church Slavonic</a>, and locative absolute in <a href=\"/wiki/Sanskrit\" title=\"Sanskrit\">Sanskrit</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Absolute_construction&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Ablative_absolute\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ablative absolute\">Ablative absolute</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Accusative_absolute\" title=\"Accusative absolute\">Accusative absolute</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Genitive_absolute\" title=\"Genitive absolute\">Genitive absolute</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Nominative_absolute\" title=\"Nominative absolute\">Nominative absolute</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Absolute_construction&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Merriam-Webster&#39;s_Collegiate_Dictionary-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Merriam-Webster&#39;s_Collegiate_Dictionary_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Merriam-Webster&#39;s_Collegiate_Dictionary_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"http://www.m-w.com/dictionary/absolute\">[1]</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-American_Heritage_Dictionary-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-American_Heritage_Dictionary_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-American_Heritage_Dictionary_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">American Heritage\u00ae Dictionary of the English Language, Fourth Edition</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-CGEL-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-CGEL_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Huddleston, Rodney; Pullum, Geoffrey K. (2002). <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Cambridge_Grammar_of_the_English_Language\" title=\"The Cambridge Grammar of the English Language\">The Cambridge Grammar of the English Language</a></i>. Cambridge, UK: <a href=\"/wiki/Cambridge_University_Press\" title=\"Cambridge University Press\">Cambridge University Press</a>. pp.&#160;1265\u20136. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-521-43146-8\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-521-43146-8\">0-521-43146-8</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Ak